{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517685"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:55:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:55:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12826"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12826"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.02,0.68,0.01,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5269"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5269"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62818"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11605"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42820"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man is brought into the emergency department (ED) by his worried partner, after she returned home to find him agitated and confused. She explains that he was in the garage working on his car when she left to walk the dog. When she returned 30 minutes later, she found him slumped on the floor, next to the car with its engine running, agitated, confused and complaining of a gradually worsening headache.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpon arrival in the ED, he is oriented to person and time but not place. He is unable to recollect how he ended up on the floor of the garage but denies any head strike. His blood pressure is 96/72 mmHg, pulse 98/min, respiratory rate 22/min and SpO2 is 95% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endotracheal intubation","Nebulised adrenaline","High flow oxygen","Direct laryngoscopy","Arterial blood gas"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is almost certainly suffering from carbon monoxide poisoning, a common source of which is a car exhaust leak. This can often present with symptoms such as dizziness, altered mental state, headache, nausea and vomiting. The SpO2 value is deceivingly high as oximeters are unable to distinguish between carboxyhaemoglobin and oxyhaemoglobin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there is a high suspicion of carbon monoxide poisoning, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh flow oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E must be started immediately. This must not be delayed for diagnostic confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt this point in time, \u003Cstrong\u003Eendotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E is not required as the patient is talking and able to protect his own airway. However, this may be necessary if his airway or breathing is compromised by a drop in consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENebulised adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is not an appropriate treatment for carbon monoxide poisoning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAirway examination via \u003Cstrong\u003Edirect laryngoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E may be required if an inhalation injury is suspected. However, this would not be the immediate priority in this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Earterial blood gas\u003C/strong\u003E may be taken to check for carboxyhemoglobin levels. However, oxygen therapy should not be delayed for this.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbon monoxide poisoning can present with symptoms such as dizziness, altered mental state, headache, nausea and vomiting","Patients with suspected carbon monoxide must be managed immediately with high flow oxygen"],"references":["Chiew AL, Buckley NA. Carbon monoxide poisoning in the 21st century. Crit Care. 2014;18(2):221. doi: 10.1186/cc13846. Epub 2014 Apr 28. PMCID: PMC4057251.","Therapeutic guidelines: Carbon monoxide poisoning. Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines. [Internet]. Accessed on 6 Jan 2025. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/etgcomplete","Chenoweth JA, Albertson TE, Greer MR. Carbon Monoxide Poisoning. Crit Care Clin. 2021 Jul;37(3):657-672. doi: 10.1016/j.ccc.2021.03.010. PMID: 34053712.","Erratum: Carbon Monoxide Poisoning: Pathogenesis, Management, and Future Directions of Therapy. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2017 Aug 1;196(3):398-399. doi: 10.1164/rccm.1963erratum. Erratum for: Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2017 Mar 1;195(5):596-606. doi: 10.1164/rccm.201606-1275CI. PMID: 28762790; PMCID: PMC6850563."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62818"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12826"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62818"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T15:54:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T15:54:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5269"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77311"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"